    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-05-29T03:11:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-05-29T03:11:00-05:00" n="298"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d298">
                <head>298. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in the Soviet Union</gloss>
                    to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d298fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Country Files, Box 719, Europe,
                            <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>, Vol. XXII, May 1972. Secret;
                            <gloss target="#t_NODIS1">Nodis</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Moscow</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1972-05-29T08:11:00+00:00">May 29, 1972, 0811Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Secto 53. Subject: Memorandum of Conversation Between Secretary and Gromyko.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Following is cleared memcon between Secretary and <persName
                            corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName>, May 25.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Memorandum of conversation</item>
                </list>
                <pb facs="1246" n="1217" xml:id="pg_1217"/>
                <p>Date: May 25, 1972</p>
                <p>Time: 4:15–4:55 pm</p>
                <p>Place: St. Catherine’s Hall, Grand Kremlin Palace, Moscow</p>
                <p>Subject: Middle East and Bilateral Issues</p>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>Participants:</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>
                        <list>
                            <item>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HMJA1">Hillenbrand</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MJFJ1">Matlock</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>
                        <list>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Andrei Gromyko</persName>, <gloss
                                    target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss> Minister of Foreign
                                Affairs</item>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_DAF1">Anatoly Dobrynin</persName>, Ambassador
                                of <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss> in <gloss target="#t_US1"
                                    >US</gloss>
                            </item>
                            <item>G.M. Korniyenko, Chief, USA, Division, MFA</item>
                            <item>Eduard Zaitsev, Interpreter</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>Middle East</p>
                <p>The Secretary asked whether <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName>
                    desired a discussion of the Middle East. <persName corresp="#p_GAA1"
                        >Gromyko</persName> indicated that unless we have new proposals, a
                    discussion of the Middle East probably would not be necessary. As for the Soviet
                    Union, it still favors Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_JGV1"
                    >Jarring</persName>’s mission. The Secretary said we are still looking for a
                        “<persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> plan.” <persName
                        corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> merely commented that he had informed
                    the Secretary last fall that he doubted the workability of <gloss
                        target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> proposals.</p>
                <p>Soviet Jewry</p>
                <p>While on the subject of the Middle East, the Secretary expressed our
                    gratification for the increased emigration from the Soviet Union to Israel and
                    said that we hope this emigration will be allowed to continue and increase.
                        <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> asked rhetorically if such
                    comments do not constitute interference in Soviet internal affairs.</p>
                <p>Representation List</p>
                <p>The Secretary then presented <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> with
                    a list of 70 persons who wish to join relatives in the United States, as a
                    supplement to the list presented to Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DAF1"
                        >Dobrynin</persName> in April. <persName corresp="#p_GAA1"
                        >Gromyko</persName> accepted the list, but stated that he did so without
                    obligation, since the Soviet Government will be guided by <gloss
                        target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss> law. As the meeting ended, <persName
                        corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> handed the list to Korniyenko.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rogers</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
